WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6-8 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

4
00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:12.000
I'm Neil.

5
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
And I'm Beth.

6
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.000
In every language there's one word which has special power over us.

7
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:19.000
Our name.

8
00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:24.000
Our senses, feelings, and whole identity are closely linked to our name.

9
00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Yet strangely our name isn't usually something we choose.

10
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:30.000
It's given to us by our parents.

11
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:34.000
But what if the name you are given at birth doesn't fit?

12
00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Maybe you simply don't like it.

13
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:41.000
Or maybe there are bigger reasons for wanting to change your name.

14
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Reasons connected with historical injustices or unfair events in the past.

15
00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:55.000
In this program, we'll be meeting two people who's family history has caused them to consider changing their name.

16
00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:00.000
And as usual, we'll be learning some useful new vocabulary as well.

17
00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:01.000
Sounds good, Beth.

18
00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:04.000
But first I have a question for you.

19
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:05.000
My name, Neil.

20
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.000
It is a British name and was given to me at birth.

21
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
But names change a lot between cultures and religions.

22
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Many Muslim boys are named Muhammad.

23
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.000
Indian boys are often called Ram or Krishna.

24
00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:21.000
And in Mexico some boys are named Hezus.

25
00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:27.000
So according to a recent global survey, what is currently the world's most popular boys name?

26
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Is it A, Hezus, B, Muhammad or C, Noah?

27
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:35.000
Hmm, I guess it's Muhammad.

28
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:39.000
Okay, Beth, I'll reveal the answer at the end of the program.

29
00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:44.000
In Britain, a person's first name is also called their Christian name.

30
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
And in Christianity many names have a religious meaning.

31
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
The name John, for example, means God is good.

32
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.000
Anderson Jeremiah is the Bishop of Edmonton.

33
00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:00.000
He was born in South India, but he doesn't have a traditional Indian sounding name.

34
00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Here, Bishop Jeremiah explains the roots of his name to BBC World Service program Heart and Soul.

35
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:10.000
It was a name of one, John Anderson.

36
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:17.000
He was the first educational missionary who came and worked and set up several schools in South India,

37
00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:28.000
who had very noble ambitions, but also as with any missionaries, he was a big collaborator of the colonial establishment at that point in time.

38
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:34.000
So he has a very strong baggage that goes with it.

39
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.000
So Anderson is my Christian name and Jeremiah is my dad's name.

40
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:45.000
Bishop Anderson Jeremiah's name comes from another man, John Anderson.

41
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:49.000
A Christian missionary during the British Empire.

42
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:55.000
The history of the British Empire in India is controversial with many views on all sides.

43
00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:02.000
Bishop Jeremiah thinks that some of the Empire's missionaries were noble, meaning admirable or morally good.

44
00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:08.000
But nevertheless, John Anderson was part of a violent and exploitative empire.

45
00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:13.000
Bishop Jeremiah uses the word baggage to describe the beliefs,

46
00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:18.000
especially outdated or unhelpful beliefs, which influence how people think.

47
00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:26.000
Emotional baggage tends to influence the feelings of one individual, while historical baggage can affect whole societies.

48
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:32.000
In India, names serve an important purpose to signify social status.

49
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:37.000
Low status Indians, including Bishop Anderson's grandparents,

50
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:45.000
is scoped social discrimination by converting to Christianity and taking another Christian name.

51
00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:52.000
But elsewhere in the British Empire, names were connected with something completely un-Christian, slavery.

52
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:59.000
Black British writer Professor Robert Beckford is an activist theologian at the University of Winchester.

53
00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:06.000
His surname, Beckford, is a slave name, passed down from his enslaved African ancestors in 18th century Jamaica.

54
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Here, Professor Beckford talks to BBC World Service Program, Hath and Soul, about his decision to name his son, Micah.

55
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:20.000
And before my son is named Micah, Micah Beckford, after one of the prophets.

56
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:28.000
So I do like the idea of people in the biblical tradition who speak truth to power, who ruffle people's feathers, who challenge the injustice.

57
00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:38.000
I haven't thought of giving myself a biblical name. I could never find a name that really resonated with me.

58
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:49.000
The phrase to speak truth to power describes times when people non-violently resist an oppressive force, such as a government or corporation, by telling the truth.

59
00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:53.000
And if you ruffle someone's feathers, you upset or annoy them.

60
00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:59.000
Maybe it's not so much your name as what you do with it that counts.

61
00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:03.000
Anyway, it's time to reveal the answer to your question, Neil.

62
00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Yes, I asked you which boy's name is currently the world's most popular and you guessed Muhammad, which was the correct answer.

63
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:19.000
Right, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned, starting with injustice, a situation lacking fairness or justice.

64
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:25.000
In British English, your Christian name is your first name, the name you are given at birth.

65
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:29.000
The adjective noble means admirable or morally good.

66
00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:38.000
Baggage refers to beliefs and feelings, especially outdated or unhelpful ones, which influence how someone thinks.

67
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:47.000
The idiom speak truth to power describes when people non-violently resist an oppressive force, such as a government or corporation by telling the truth.

68
00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:53.000
And finally, to ruffle someone's feathers means to upset or annoy them.

69
00:05:53.000 --> 00:06:03.000
Once again, our six minutes are up, but remember to join us again next time for more trending topics and useful vocabulary here at six minutes English.

70
00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Goodbye for now.

71
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Bye.

72
00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:09.000
6.8 English

73
00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:11.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com
